    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3732435717" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3732435717" />
    <a title="Ross Blocher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10407443-ross-blocher"><img alt="Ross Blocher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1340636529p2/10407443.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3732435717?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ross Blocher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ross Blocher" href="/user/show/10407443-ross-blocher">Ross Blocher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3732435717" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14419473264619479906"><i>Cooked</i> is Michael Pollan&apos;s love letter to food preparation. In our world of fast food, ubiquitous restaurants, frozen entrees and meal delivery, he wants to remind us of the good old days when we spent significant portions of our time getting food on the table. Pollan references the average family&apos;s daily time spent cooking and cleaning up - 27 minutes and 4 minutes, respectively - roughly half what it was when he was a boy in the 60s. Corporations have stepped in to make food preparation easy f</span>
  <span id="freeText14419473264619479906" style="display:none"><i>Cooked</i> is Michael Pollan's love letter to food preparation. In our world of fast food, ubiquitous restaurants, frozen entrees and meal delivery, he wants to remind us of the good old days when we spent significant portions of our time getting food on the table. Pollan references the average family's daily time spent cooking and cleaning up - 27 minutes and 4 minutes, respectively - roughly half what it was when he was a boy in the 60s. Corporations have stepped in to make food preparation easy for us, freeing us [mostly women, historically] to do other things. While there are benefits to this progress, Pollan wants to advocate for an increased understanding of, appreciation for, and connection to what we eat.<br /><br />Pollan approaches cooking from every angle he can: the history of food and what we know from tradition and archaeology, the chemistry of food transformation, the science of sustenance and nutrition, the history of various cooking methods and cultural practices, and the execution of cooking itself. He's found a clever organizing schema that will stick easily in readers' minds: Fire, Water, Air and Earth. He'll admit that the classical elements don't break down as cleanly as one might hope (cooking with water involves heating that water with fire, the air chapter involves the fungi we meet again in the earth chapter, we now have other ways of generating heat, and so forth), but I'll grant the clever mnemonic. For each category, he teams up with a professional and/or influential cook to ask questions, tell stories, and interactively learn their craft. For fire, it's a barbeque pitmaster. For water, it's a braising specialist. For air, it's breadmaking (I probably enjoyed this section the most). For earth, it's managing the tricky balance of fermentation and bacterial cultures.<br /><br />Despite Pollan's general engagement, this book did feel somewhat like a formulaic, checklist-completion venture to me. I have a hard time putting my thumb on precisely what gave me this impression, but it just felt like Pollan gave himself an assignment, broke it logically into pieces, conducted the required research, gave interviews and signed up for experiences, and dutifully passed these elements along to us in often-florid prose. There's nothing particularly wrong with any of that, but it did throttle the sense of passion and spontaneity. I was reading this on vacation and didn't immediately drop everything to acquire my own bread starter, but if anything would inspire me to be a more active cook, it would probably be something like <i>Cooked</i>. At the very least, this gave me some sweet new knowledge with which to savor my meals, more respect for the food preparers in my life, and a renewed appreciation for the elaborate chemical processes and received knowledge harnessed in the effort.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14419473264619479906" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

