    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3391375462" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3391375462" />
    <a title="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58567012-ann-marie-cookie-m"><img alt="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607273374p2/58567012.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3391375462?book_show_action=true">Aug 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" href="/user/show/58567012-ann-marie-cookie-m">Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/17368465-cooked">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3391375462" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4501993777953871156">I have a funny relationship with Michael Pollan&apos;s books. I never actually want to read them. I can think of nothing more tedious than to examine in fine detail the aspects of food and the eating of it the way he does.<br/> <br/>Yet, once I start reading I get so involved I cannot help but see myself, my family, my ancestors, the generations to follow me living in his narrative.<br/><br/> This holds so true for &quot;Cooked.&quot; I started cooking at the age of 6 or 7 , but was probably born interested in it in ways I now se</span>
  <span id="freeText4501993777953871156" style="display:none">I have a funny relationship with Michael Pollan's books. I never actually want to read them. I can think of nothing more tedious than to examine in fine detail the aspects of food and the eating of it the way he does.<br /> <br />Yet, once I start reading I get so involved I cannot help but see myself, my family, my ancestors, the generations to follow me living in his narrative.<br /><br /> This holds so true for "Cooked." I started cooking at the age of 6 or 7 , but was probably born interested in it in ways I now see as going beyond the girly, mommy-type games of family care. It has always been tied up in family history, science and competition for me. I won 2nd place in a Council wide, 2 county Girl Scout bake off when I was 10 years old, with only the second came I had ever baked! Go me! I lost to a girl 3 years older than me with the remarkable name of Paisley Woodside.<br /> <br />So, anyway... I connected with most sections of Pollan's book, the parts about bread baking, cooking with water (braising), fermenting, but not the cooking with fire bits. In our family cooking with fire meant Daddy cremating a cut up fryer chicken on the grill until the skin was black, the inside was tough and he called it, for some unknown reason, pelican steak.<br /> <br /> My mom made our bread every week, she pickled, canned and preserved anything edible that grew within a 5 mile range of our house, and although we never brewed beer, she did attempt sauerkraut once with my paternal grandfather's vintage Red Wing crock. It was a bust. The kraut may have been delicious, but nobody in our family liked sauerkraut then, although today I wouldn't eat a bratwurst without loads of it.<br /> <br />Pollan really gets into the evolution and history, the whys of how these methods of cooking are so much a part of our genetic soul.<br /> <br />The end of the book includes some of the recipes he learned in his journey toward understanding why cooking out food is so integral to our well being and survival.<br /> <br /> We may once have been creatures that survived on a raw diet, but we are tens of thousands of years beyond those beings, with digestive systems that depend on cooking's role in breaking down our nourishment into a useable form.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4501993777953871156" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

